rtment. All information is taken from looked after children statistical first releases, which can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-looked-after-children" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-looked-after-children</a>.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","46762 ; 46763","2016-10-17T14:53:51.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595546/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595546/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595546/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-07","GCSE: Children in Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what proportion of looked-after children in (a) Woking constituency, (b) Surrey, (c) the South East and (d) the UK have achieved at least five GCSEs at grade A* to C in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Mr Jonathan Lord","Woking","Mr Jonathan Lord","46753"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595547","Department for Education","false","2016-10-19","<p>The Department collects data from local authorities in England on how many parents received an offer of a place for their children at one of their preferred secondary or primary schools based on the respective national offer days.</p><p>The most recent data relate to the start of the 2016/17 academic year. Figures on the number of children who secured a place at their first choice school for the local authority of Surrey, the region of the South East and for England, are outlined below.</p><p>Figures for the UK are not available as Northern Ireland, Wales and Scotland run their own separate school application and offer processes.</p><p> </p><p><strong>Number of applications and first choice offers for entry into primary and secondary school for academic year 2016/17</strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>Surrey</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>South East</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>England</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Number of applications for a primary school place </strong></p></td><td><p>13,859</p></td><td><p>104,635</p></td><td><p>641,572</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Of which: number offered their first choice</p></td><td><p>11,394</p></td><td><p>90,790</p></td><td><p>566,836</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Percentage offered their first choice</p></td><td><p>82.2</p></td><td><p>86.6</p></td><td><p>88.4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Number of applications for a secondary school place </strong></p></td><td><p>11,154</p></td><td><p>88,724</p></td><td><p>548,006</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Of which: number offered their first choice</p></td><td><p>9,404</p></td><td><p>76,801</p></td><td><p>460,836</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Percentage offered their first choice</p></td><td><p>84.3</p></td><td><p>86.6</p></td><td><p>84.1</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-10-19T16:19:04.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595547/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595547/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595547/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-07","Schools: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many children secured a place at their first choice school in (a) Woking constituency, (b) Surrey, (c) the South East and (d) the UK in the latest period for which data is available.","false","Biography information for Mr Jonathan Lord","Woking","Mr Jonathan Lord","46755"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595548","Department for Education","false","2016-10-17","<p>We will announce more detail on the funding for alternative provision under the new commissioning arrangements in due course. We are mindful of the diverse range of provision which comes under the banner of alternative provision, and the particular logistical and geographical issues related to hospital schools.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-10-17T14:49:27.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595548/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595548/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595548/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-07","Schools: Hospitals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how existing schools embedded in hospitals for pupils with medical needs will be supported financially if planned changes to the commissioning of alternative provision proceed; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Chris Leslie","Nottingham East","Chris Leslie","46776"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595549","Department for Education","false","2016-10-17","<p>Information on the percentage of pupils who are eligible for free school meals and achieved five GCSEs at grades A*- C, in each local authority area and at regional level in England for each of the last six years is published as part of the GCSE and equivalent results, and the attainment by pupil characteristics statistical first releases (SFRs)[1] [2]. Parliamentary constituency level information is not available.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Education produces statistics on England only. The responsibility for education statistics in Northern Ireland, Scotland and Wales lies with each devolved administration.</p><p> </p><p>[1] KS4 SFR 2014/15: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/493475/SFR01_2016_LA_Tables.xlsx" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/493475/SFR01_2016_LA_Tables.xlsx</a> (Table LA8)</p><p> </p><p>[2] KS4 SFR: Years: 2009/10 to 2013/14:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/402634/SFR06_2015_National_and_LA.xls" target="_blank"> https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/gcse-and-equivalent-attainment-by-pupil-characteristics-2014</a> (table 5)</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-10-17T14:51:15.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595549/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595549/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595549/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-07","GCSE: Disadvantaged","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what proportion of children who receive free school meals in (a) Woking constituency, (b) Surrey, (c) the South East and (d) the UK have achieved at least five GCSEs at grades A*-C in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Mr Jonathan Lord","Woking","Mr Jonathan Lord","46764"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595550","Department for Education","false","2016-10-17","<p>Providing young people with the right information at the right time is key to ensuring every young person goes as far as their talents will take them. This is why we are investing £90 million over this Parliament to ensure that every young person has equal access to the life-changing advice and inspiration they need to fulfil their potential and succeed in life. This includes £20 million to increase the number of mentors from the world of work, supporting 25,000 young people a year by 2020. We also fund the National Careers Service, which received £77 million in 2016/17, to provide careers advice to young people via the National Contact Centre and the National Careers Service website. The vast majority of people (87%) were happy with the service they received using the website.</p><p> </p><p>We need to make available the support to help young people negotiate this information and to help guide them through the decision-making process. Maintained schools must ensure that pupils receive independent careers advice and that this is presented in an impartial manner; includes information on the range of education or training options and promotes the best interests of the pupils to whom it is given. We know that pupils can gain confidence and motivation from the opportunity to explore career ideas through individual, face-to-face discussions with a range of people, including careers professionals. We trust schools to know what is best for their pupils and to tailor what they offer and who delivers it.</p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon",,"2016-10-17T16:01:34.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595550/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595550/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595550/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-07","Vocational Guidance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what recent steps she has taken to ensure that children have access to professional careers advice in schools.","false","Biography information for Mr Jonathan Lord","Woking","Mr Jonathan Lord","46759"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595551","Department for Education","false","2016-10-17","<p>The requested information on children who receive free school meals at A-Level in England is not held by the Department. The Department for Education produces statistics on England only. The responsibility for education statistics in Northern Ireland, Scotland and Wales lies with each devolved administration.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-10-17T14:46:57.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595551/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595551/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595551/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-07","GCE A-level: Disadvantaged","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what proportion of children who receive free school meals in (a) Woking constituency, (b) Surrey, (c) the South East and (d) the UK have studied A-Levels in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Mr Jonathan Lord","Woking","Mr Jonathan Lord","46760"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595552","Department for Education","false","2016-11-01","<p>The Department for Education does not keep a central record of legal cases by type.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-11-01T14:21:43.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595552/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595552/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595552/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-07","Academies: Civil Proceedings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many legal cases have been brought against her Department by academy trusts in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jess Phillips","Birmingham, Yardley","Jess Phillips","46707"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595553","Department for Education","false","2016-10-19","<p>The Secretary of State for Education has authorised the Parliamentary Under Secretary of State for Schools and eight regional schools commissioners (RSCs) to act on her behalf on the approval or rejection of applications for maintained schools to convert to academy status. RSCs are Director level civil servants; the Secretary of State remains accountable for, and has the power to overturn, their decisions. RSCs must make their decisions in line with a Decision Making Framework, which has been determined by ministers. The Decision Making Framework is published on gov.uk at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/548540/RSC_Decision_Making_Framework_April_2016.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/548540/RSC_Decision_Making_Framework_April_2016.pdf</a></p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-10-19T16:17:53.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595553/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595553/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595553/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-07","Academies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 15 September 2016 to Question 45512, what grades of officials and which Ministers have the authority to make decisions on the approval or rejection of applications from maintained schools to convert to academy status.","false","Biography information for Jess Phillips","Birmingham, Yardley","Jess Phillips","46745"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595554","Department for Education","false","2016-11-02","<p>Any measures to protect children where they are attending privately run classes, including those provided on private property, rest entirely with parents. It is a matter of parental choice to allow their children to attend and to make a considered decision about the suitability of the individuals running the class.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-11-02T17:29:01.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595554/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595554/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595554/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-07","Extracurricular Activities: Offenders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 15 September 2016 to Question 45985 on extracurricular activities: offenders, what measures are in place to protect children when such classes are provided (a) privately and (b) on private property.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","46702"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595555","Department for Education","false","2016-10-19","<p>The Department for Education has never required the use of socket covers in schools. All socket outlets in teaching areas of schools are designed to BS1363 and have built in safety shutters.</p><p> </p><p>The Department of Health guidance followed recent advice from electrical engineers that in some circumstances socket covers can compromise the safe operation of socket outlets and advises against their use.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-10-19T16:21:09.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595555/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595555/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595555/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-07","Schools: Electrical Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment her Department has made of the implications for its policies of the decision by the Department of Health to remove electrical socket inserts from all premises where NHS care is delivered; and whether her Department plans to issue similar guidance.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","46978"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595556","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-12","<p>In his announcement on 13 August the Chancellor guaranteed that structural and investment funds projects, including ESF, signed before the Autumn Statement, would be fully funded. The agreement with the National Offender Management Service is covered by this guarantee. The Chancellor extended the guarantee in his announcement on 3 October. The Chancellor confirmed that the government will guarantee EU funding for structural and investment fund projects, including agri-environment schemes, signed after the Autumn Statement and which continue after we have left the EU provided that these deliver good value for money and are in line with domestic strategic priorities.</p><p>The administration of the European Social Fund in Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland is the responsibility of the devolved administrations. Where the devolved administrations sign up to structural and investment fund projects under their current EU budget allocation prior to leaving the EU, the government has confirmed that it will ensure they are funded to meet the announced commitments.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","46966 ; 46973","2016-10-12T16:39:40.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595556/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595556/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595556/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-07","National Offender Management Service: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether employment and skills funding, announced by the Department for Work and Pensions on 26 January 2016, and allocated to the National Offender Management Service, will be guaranteed after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","46972"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595557","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-12","<p>In his announcement on 13 August the Chancellor guaranteed that structural and investment funds projects, including ESF, signed before the Autumn Statement, would be fully funded. The agreement with the National Offender Management Service is covered by this guarantee. The Chancellor extended the guarantee in his announcement on 3 October. The Chancellor confirmed that the government will guarantee EU funding for structural and investment fund projects, including agri-environment schemes, signed after the Autumn Statement and which continue after we have left the EU provided that these deliver good value for money and are in line with domestic strategic priorities.</p><p>The administration of the European Social Fund in Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland is the responsibility of the devolved administrations. Where the devolved administrations sign up to structural and investment fund projects under their current EU budget allocation prior to leaving the EU, the government has confirmed that it will ensure they are funded to meet the announced commitments.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","46966 ; 46972","2016-10-12T16:39:40.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595557/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595557/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595557/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-07","Department for Education: Employment Schemes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether his Department plans to fund employment schemes that were launched on 26 January 2016 after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","46973"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595558","Department for Education","false","2016-10-17","<p>Primary and secondary schools can choose to teach the Welsh language to pupils if there is sufficient demand. It is possible for a pupil in England to take privately a Welsh language GCSE offered in Wales if an examination centre is willing to enter them. This will include a revised Welsh Second Language GCSE available for first teaching from September 2017.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-10-17T15:33:11.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595558/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595558/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595558/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-07","Welsh Language: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether she plans to facilitate the learning of the Welsh language by pupils in England.","false","Biography information for Chris Elmore","Ogmore","Chris Elmore","46891"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595559","Department for Education","false","2016-10-17","<p>The information is not held in the format requested.</p><p> </p><p>Table 6a of the Initial Teacher Training Performance Profiles details the employment outcomes within six months of being awarded Qualified Teacher Status of those who were trained to teach modern and ancient foreign languages. This includes employment in all sectors: state, independent and sector not known.</p><p> </p><p>The data is available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/initial-teacher-training-performance-profiles-2014-to-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/initial-teacher-training-performance-profiles-2014-to-2015</a></p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-10-17T15:33:54.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595559/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595559/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595559/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-07","Teachers: Languages","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 12 September 2016 to Question 44304, what information her Department holds on the number of language graduates who have entered the teaching profession in each of the last six years.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","46908"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595560","Department for Education","false","2016-10-12","<p>Departmental funding rules require full time students with prior attainment of a D to work towards achieving a C grade or higher in GCSE English and maths. Students who achieve lower than a D grade at 16 may study other qualifications such as Functional Skills as a ‘stepping stone’ towards GCSE.</p><p> </p><p>For those opting to retake their GCSE(s) or being required to do so due to having previously attained a grade D, there is no requirement for them to repeatedly re-sit the GCSE exam. Schools and colleges have the freedom to determine when a student is ready to re-sit their GCSE. This is because our 16-19 English and maths requirements relates to enrolments rather than exam entries. This provides a school or college the flexibility to determine when best for a student to be entered for and sit an exam. For some students that might be the following November, while other students may require</p><p>a year, or two years study and tuition before they are ready to re-sit the exam.</p><p> </p><p>If students resit their GCSE part way through their programme and fail to gain a grade C then they are expected to continue studying for the GCSE.</p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon",,"2016-10-12T11:49:04.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595560/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595560/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595560/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-07","GCSE: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether students who have not achieved at least a C grade in English and mathematics GCSE will be required to resit those exams as many times as it takes them to achieve that grade.","false","Biography information for Dr Tania Mathias","Twickenham","Dr Tania Mathias","46941"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595561","Department for Education","false","2016-10-12","<p>Funding for the study of English and maths, including GCSE resits, is provided through the 16-19 national funding formula. The formula incorporates disadvantage funding for providers including a funding uplift of up to £960 per full time student per year to provide for the additional costs incurred for teaching students who have low prior attainment, as indicated by not achieving English and/or maths GCSEs at grade C or above by the end of year 11 (typically age 16). This additional funding is not intended to solely fund maths and English qualifications, but to fund support for students to achieve their learning goals, including maths and English.</p><p> </p><p>For the past three years the Government has also invested in programmes to support improvements in the teaching of maths and English in Further Education (FE) settings. This year, funding will provide up to 13,000 training opportunities for FE practitioners to improve their subject knowledge and confidence in their teaching of maths or English, fund bursaries for 300 graduates to train to become maths or English teachers in FE settings and further build evidence on evidence of what constitutes effective delivery and teaching of English and maths for students aged 16 to 18 that have not yet achieved level 2 English and maths.</p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon",,"2016-10-12T11:50:10.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595561/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595561/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595561/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-07","Further Education: GCSE","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what additional resources are being provided for post-16 students who are required to resit English and mathematics GCSEs.","false","Biography information for Dr Tania Mathias","Twickenham","Dr Tania Mathias","46939"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595562","Department for Education","false","2016-11-11","<p>We have been clear that we want to see all schools, over time, become academies. But our focus is on schools where standards need to be raised. So we will continue to convert all schools that are judged inadequate by Ofsted, and work with those that are coasting or otherwise underperforming to identify the support they need to improve. We expect that in some cases this support will be through conversion to become a sponsored academy. No new legislation is required for these purposes.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","47545","2016-11-11T12:27:01.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595562/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595562/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595562/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-07","Academies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether she plans to bring forward legislation to allow for the forcible conversion of schools to academy status in underperforming local authority areas.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","47393"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595563","Department for Education","false","2016-10-17","<p>All Government Departments are bound by legal requirements concerning the right to work in the UK and, in addition, the Civil Service Nationality Rules.</p><p> </p><p>Evidence of nationality is checked at the point of recruitment into the Civil Service as part of wider pre-employment checks, but there is no requirement on departments to retain this information beyond the point at which it has served its purpose.</p><p> </p><p>More broadly, the Government will be consulting in due course on how we work with business to ensure that workers in this country have the skills that they need to get a job. However, there are no proposals to publish lists of the number or proportion of foreign workers.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","47412 ; 47559 ; 47581","2016-10-17T16:32:54.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595563/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595563/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595563/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-07","Department for Education: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, (a) how many and (b) what proportion of staff employed by her Department are non-UK nationals.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","47395"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595564","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-20","<p>The Bologna Process, which created the European Higher Education Area in 2010, is an intergovernmental agreement among 28 countries in the European region. It is not an EU body and therefore UK membership will not be affected by the UK’s departure from the EU.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-10-20T16:06:21.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595564/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595564/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595564/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-07","Higher Education: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if the Government plans to remain a signatory of the Bologna Declaration after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","47399"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595565","Department for Education","false","2016-10-17","<p>Apprenticeships are a crucial way to develop the skills needed by employers. There is strong evidence that apprenticeships are already a good prospect for investment in terms of returns to individuals, to businesses and to Government. For each pound the Government invests in Level 2 and Level 3 adult apprenticeships, we receive economic benefits of £26 and £28 respectively over the rest of the learners’ working lives.</p><p> </p><p>By increasing the quality and quantity of apprenticeships to reach our commitment of 3 million starts in England by 2020, our goal is to secure greater benefits for more apprentices, employers and our economy. To increase numbers and improve access, we are focussing the work of the National Apprenticeships Service on communicating the benefits, and building strong relationships with a wider range of employers and intermediaries.</p><p> </p><p>The 2020 Vision sets out the key elements of our strategy to further address skills shortages and stimulate economic growth through reforms to apprenticeships. .</p><p> </p><p>Our strategy gives employers the opportunity to develop new apprenticeship standards to meet the skills needs of their sector. By increasing the relevance and quality of apprenticeships and developing the skills of workers, standards will ensure employers have the opportunity to develop and access the skills they need.</p><p> </p><p>We are focusing development of apprenticeship standards where employers identify a skills need and demand exists, subject to suitability. In giving employers this freedom, we have seen increased appetite for standards at higher levels, where we know they add the most value. We have also seen standards developed in sectors where they have not been used before, ensuring the benefits are felt across the economy.</p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon","46788","2016-10-17T16:11:07.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595565/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595565/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595565/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-07","Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 13 September 2016 to Question 46284, what assessment she has made of the effect of apprenticeship standards on the productivity and growth of the UK economy.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","47388"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595566","Department for Education","false","2016-10-17","<p>Employers are already designing high-quality apprenticeships across a range of occupations to meet their skills needs. More than 1,400 employers are involved with 260 new apprenticeships standards already published and more than 180 are in development.</p><p>Employers are in the best position to determine the skills they need and we will work with them as the Apprenticeship Levy is introduced, and as the wider approach to the Industrial Strategy is developed, to ensure their needs are met and more opportunities are created for apprentices of all ages and from all backgrounds.</p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon",,"2016-10-17T15:46:06.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595566/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595566/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595566/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-07","Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 13 September 2016 to Question 46284, on apprentices, what steps her Department is taking to ensure the new standards are developed in areas where skills shortages exist in the economy.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","47389"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595567","Department for Education","false","2016-10-25","<p>The autumn school census is undertaken on the first Thursday in October. The census guide was made available on the Department’s website on 4 May 2016. Five months’ notice was provided to parents by this document. The guidance can be found here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/school-census-2016-to-2017-guide-for-schools-and-las" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/school-census-2016-to-2017-guide-for-schools-and-las</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The census specifications were first set out in technical terms to the public on the Department’s website via the business and technical specifications, which are primarily used by suppliers of school’s management information systems, on 18 December 2015. As such, some 10 months’ notice was provided via this document. The specifications can be found here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/school-census-2016-to-2017-technical-information" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/school-census-2016-to-2017-technical-information</a>.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-10-25T16:08:34.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595567/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595567/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595567/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-07","Schools: Census","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much notice was given to parents of the school census conducted in September and October 2016.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","47424"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595568","Department for Education","false","2016-10-12","<p>It is for schools to decide how best to deliver the curriculum. They can teach about gender issues through personal, social, health and economic (PSHE) education, which is a non-statutory curriculum subject. The non-statutory PSHE programme of study, issued by the PSHE Association, includes teaching pupils about gender issues.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-10-12T14:23:49.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595568/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595568/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595568/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-07","Personal, Social, Health and Economic Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, for what reason gender issues are not a compulsory part of the PSHE curriculum; and whether she has any plans to so introduce such issues into that curriculum.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","47426"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595569","Department for Education","false","2016-10-13","<p>We understand that some organisations want to delay or scrap the levy, but any delay would mean holding back opportunities for people and businesses to gain the skills they need. We are working with the CBI, employers and training providers to make sure the new system works for them. In August we published proposals for how apprenticeships will be paid for in England in the future and invited feedback on these. Following thorough analysis we will publish final details at the end of October.</p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon",,"2016-10-13T15:08:29.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595569/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595569/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595569/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-07","Apprentices: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment her Department has made of the potential merits of the flexibility of the scheme of the CBI's proposal to delay implementation of the apprenticeship levy.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","47366"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595570","Department for Education","false","2016-10-24","<p>Please see the table below showing the number and percentage of pupils attending outstanding schools, for areas with different selective policies. Data is given as at 31 March 2016.</p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="4"><p><strong>Pupils at mainstream state-funded secondary schools</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="3"><p><strong>Latest Ofsted inspection data as at 31 March 2016</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Total number of pupils in Ofsted rated schools</p></td><td><p>Number of pupils in schools rated outstanding</p></td><td><p>Percentage of pupils in schools rated outstanding</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Pupils attending secondary schools in fully selective areas<sup>1</sup></p></td><td><p>282,608</p></td><td><p>100,308</p></td><td><p>35</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Pupils attending secondary schools in other areas with selective schools<sup>2</sup></p></td><td><p>703,417</p></td><td><p>205,097</p></td><td><p>29</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Pupils attending secondary schools in areas with no selective schools</p></td><td><p>2,077,665</p></td><td><p>488,673</p></td><td><p>24</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2"><p>Source: Ofsted official statistics from 31 March 2016</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Notes: 1. Includes selective schools in the following areas which operate area wide arrangements for academic selection: Bexley, Buckinghamshire, Kent, Lincolnshire, Medway, Slough, Southend, Sutton, Torbay and Trafford. 2. Includes schools in twenty-six local authorities that have selective schools operating their own arrangements for academic selection.</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="4" rowspan="2"><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="4"><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-10-24T16:38:03.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595570/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595570/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595570/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-07","Schools: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what proportion of total secondary school places in (a) areas with selective policies and (b) other areas are in schools rated outstanding.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","47367"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595571","Department for Education","false","2016-11-11","<p>Parliamentary questions 43736, 43737, 43738 were answered on 01 November 2016.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","48230","2016-11-11T12:22:07.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595571/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595571/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595571/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-07","Department for Education: Written Questions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, when she plans to answer Question 43738, tabled on 20 July 2016 by the right hon. Member for East Ham.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","47369"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595572","Department for Education","false","2016-10-17","<p>The national funding formula will ensure that all children, whatever their background, are supported to achieve their full potential. Children from deprived backgrounds will attract funding in addition to the basic per pupil amount so that they get the extra help they need to succeed. We will also continue to provide targeted funding through the pupil premium, worth £2.5 billion this year.</p><p> </p><p>We proposed in the first stage of the national funding formula consultation to use a combined pupil-and area-level deprivation measure in the formula to best identify those children and schools that need additional support. We will put forward our detailed proposals in the next stage of consultation later this year.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-10-17T15:32:33.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595572/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595572/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595572/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-07","Schools: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps she is taking to ensure that the introduction of a new national funding formula will prioritise schools in disadvantaged areas for the allocation of funding.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","47391"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595573","Department for Education","false","2016-10-18","<p>The Higher Education Council for Funding in England (HEFCE) reports that the HE sector was in sound financial health in 2014/15. In the same academic year, overseas fee income accounted for nearly 13% of total sector income on average. The report can be found on HEFCE’s website at: <a href="http://www.hefce.ac.uk/media/HEFCE,2014/Content/Pubs/2016/201604/HEFCE2016_04.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.hefce.ac.uk/media/HEFCE,2014/Content/Pubs/2016/201604/HEFCE2016_04.pdf</a></p><p>International students make an important economic and cultural contribution to the UK. The UK has, and will continue to have, a world class education system that attracts students from across the world.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-10-18T13:37:53.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595573/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595573/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595573/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-07","Higher Education: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment she has made of the effect of a reduction in international student numbers on university finances.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","47306"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595574","Department for Education","false","2016-10-18","<p>Department for Education officials meet regularly with Home Office officials to discuss a range of issues regarding EU students and staff. The two departments will continue to work closely as these issues progress.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-10-18T16:03:47.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595574/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595574/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595574/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-07","Higher Education: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what recent discussions she has had with the Home Secretary on work permits and immigration rules for EU citizens working in higher education, research and academia after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","47297"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595575","Department for Education","false","2016-11-01","<p>The numbers of reported school fires in Great Britain are as follows:</p><p>2005/06: 1,400</p><p>2006/07: 1,200</p><p>2007/08: 1,000</p><p>2008/09: 1,000</p><p>2009/10: -----</p><p>2010/11: 800</p><p>2011/12: 700</p><p>2012/13: 600</p><p>2013/14: 600</p><p>These are National Statistics’ figures published on GOV.UK and are rounded[1].</p><p> </p><p>There are no statistics for 2009/10 as none were published for that year due to an incomplete data set. Since 2014/15 fire statistics are published as England only, with data on ‘educational premises’ including other institutions such as colleges and universities, alongside schools, which is not consistent with the data above. These England only statistics are available on GOV.UK: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/fire-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/fire-statistics</a></p><p> </p><p>The Government does not hold data centrally on the annual cost of replacing or repairing school buildings following damage by fire. However, the Department is currently collecting data on both the capital costs resulting from fire damage and the costs of providing alternative accommodation.</p><p> </p><p>[1] <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/fire-statistics-great-britain-2013-to-2014" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/fire-statistics-great-britain-2013-to-2014</a></p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-11-01T17:54:16.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595575/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595575/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595575/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-07","Schools: Fires","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many school fires have been reported in each year since 2005; and what the cost has been of replacing or repairing the buildings affected by such fires in each such year.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","47265"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595576","Department for Education","false","2016-11-01","<p>All schools must promote religious tolerance and integration whatever their character and ethos. The Department is currently consulting on proposals to replace the 50% cap on faith admissions in faith free schools with new measures to better promote inclusivity and community cohesion. The proposed measures, alongside existing requirements to promote fundamental British values, will apply to all new faith free schools with 100% faith admissions and help ensure that pupils are prepared for life in modern Britain. The consultation document is available at: <a href="https://consult.education.gov.uk/school-frameworks/schools-that-work-for-everyone" target="_blank">https://consult.education.gov.uk/school-frameworks/schools-that-work-for-everyone</a></p><p> </p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-11-01T13:22:12.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595576/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595576/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595576/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-07","Free Schools: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment she has made of the effect of removing the 50 per cent cap on religious selection in free schools on religious tolerance and integration.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","47363"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595577","Department for Education","false","2016-11-01","<p>The Department is currently consulting on proposals to remove the 50% cap on faith admissions in new faith free schools. The outcome of the consultation and government response will be presented to Parliament. The consultation document, 'Schools that work for everyone', is available at: <a href="https://consult.education.gov.uk/school-frameworks/schools-that-work-for-everyone" target="_blank">https://consult.education.gov.uk/school-frameworks/schools-that-work-for-everyone</a></p><p>Any changes to the Schools Admissions Code are subject to Parliamentary scrutiny.</p><p> </p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-11-01T13:15:56.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595577/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595577/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595577/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-07","Schools: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will make it her policy to allow Parliament to vote on (a) whether to remove the current 50 per cent cap on religious selection in free schools and (b) other changes to the schools admissions code.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","47256"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595578","Department for Education","false","2016-10-17","<p>There is not a consistent metric to measure school performance at Key Stage 4 over this time period. However, the data showing the performance of schools in each of the last 15 years as measured at the time is available at the download data page of the “Compare school and college” website[1].</p><p> </p><p>[1] <a href="https://www.compare-school-performance.service.gov.uk/download-data" target="_blank">https://www.compare-school-performance.service.gov.uk/download-data</a></p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-10-17T15:34:27.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595578/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595578/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595578/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-07","Schools: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, which 20 secondary schools have had the biggest improvement in GCSE results over the last 15 years.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","47267"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595579","Department for Education","false","2016-10-12","<p>As set out in our Post 16 Skills Plan, we will take forward the recommendations of the Sainsbury Review to put in place a world-class technical option that provides preparation for highly skilled employment. The technical option will be a prestigious and high-quality option for 16 year olds as an alternative to academic study. Applied general qualifications such as BTECs are not designed to be part of the technical education option. We plan to review the contribution of these qualifications to preparing students for higher education and the impact any reform would have on widening participation. We will announce our decisions later in the year.</p><p> </p><p>It is important that individuals are able to switch between the academic and technical options so that students’ options are not closed down. Flexible learning will be important to learners of all ages, given the changing labour market. We accepted the Sainsbury panel’s recommendation that there should be appropriate bridging courses to make movement between the two options easily accessible and will be looking at options for putting these courses in place.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon","47341","2016-10-12T11:46:34.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595579/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595579/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595579/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-07","Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to the Skills Plan, what her policy is on enabling students to continue to study a mixture of both (a) academic and (b) vocational subjects.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","47340"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595580","Department for Education","false","2016-10-12","<p>As set out in our Post 16 Skills Plan, we will take forward the recommendations of the Sainsbury Review to put in place a world-class technical option that provides preparation for highly skilled employment. The technical option will be a prestigious and high-quality option for 16 year olds as an alternative to academic study. Applied general qualifications such as BTECs are not designed to be part of the technical education option. We plan to review the contribution of these qualifications to preparing students for higher education and the impact any reform would have on widening participation. We will announce our decisions later in the year.</p><p> </p><p>It is important that individuals are able to switch between the academic and technical options so that students’ options are not closed down. Flexible learning will be important to learners of all ages, given the changing labour market. We accepted the Sainsbury panel’s recommendation that there should be appropriate bridging courses to make movement between the two options easily accessible and will be looking at options for putting these courses in place.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon","47340","2016-10-12T11:46:34.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595580/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595580/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595580/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-07","Vocational Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to the Skills Plan, what her policy is on the future provision of BTECs.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","47341"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595581","Department for Education","false","2016-11-01","<p>We want a diverse range of schools to give parents greater choice and drive up standards. The proposals set out in our consultation, 'Schools that Work for Everyone', aim to increase local capacity by enabling a wider group of providers to establish new schools. The proposal to remove the 50 per cent cap on religious selection in new free schools has, for some faith groups, been a barrier to setting up new schools. The removal of the cap and the establishment of new faith schools will add to the overall stock of places and should increase choice for parents.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-11-01T13:22:45.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595581/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595581/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595581/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-07","Free Schools: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment she has made of the effect of removing the 50 per cent cap on religious selection in free schools on the ability of parents to get their children into a local school.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","47231"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595582","Department for Education","false","2016-11-01","<p>Some faith groups, including the Catholic Church, have felt unable to open new schools through the free schools route because they believe it contravenes religious rules. This has meant, for example, that in areas where there has been significant growth in the Catholic population, the Catholic Church has not set up sufficient school places to meet demand.</p><p>We want more high quality providers to be able to set up new schools and we are consulting on how best to do that. The consultation document, 'Schools that work for everyone' is available at: <a href="https://consult.education.gov.uk/school-frameworks/schools-that-work-for-everyone" target="_blank">https://consult.education.gov.uk/school-frameworks/schools-that-work-for-everyone</a></p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-11-01T13:20:24.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595582/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595582/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595582/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-07","Church Schools: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment she has made of changes to the cap on religious selection on the opening of new Catholic state schools.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","47232"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595583","Department for Education","false","2016-10-18","<p>The Universities and Colleges Admissions Service (UCAS) publishes data on applications and acceptances to full-time undergraduate courses. The table below shows the number of main scheme applications (applications submitted by 30 June each year) and the number of acceptances for ‘pre-clinical medicine’ for applicants domiciled in England.</p><p><strong>Table: applications and acceptances to pre-clinical medicine<sup>1</sup></strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>2011</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Number of acceptances</p></td><td><p>5,525</p></td><td><p>5,705</p></td><td><p>5,510</p></td><td><p>5,630</p></td><td><p>5,515</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Number of main scheme applications</p></td><td><p>55,280</p></td><td><p>53,740</p></td><td><p>54,710</p></td><td><p>55,065</p></td><td><p>48,525</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Notes:</p><p>1. Pre-clinical medicine is based on Joint Academic Coding System (JACS) code A1</p><p>The figures were extracted from the UCAS 2015 end of cycle data resources (tables DR3_017_01 and DR3_017_03) available via the following weblink:</p><p><a href="https://www.ucas.com/corporate/data-and-analysis/ucas-undergraduate-releases/ucas-undergraduate-end-cycle-data-resource-5" target="_blank">https://www.ucas.com/corporate/data-and-analysis/ucas-undergraduate-releases/ucas-undergraduate-end-cycle-data-resource-5</a></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-10-18T16:06:09.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595583/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595583/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595583/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-07","Medicine: Higher Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many applications for medicine courses were (a) received and (b) accepted at higher education institutions in England in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","47445"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595584","Department for Education","false","2016-10-17","<p>The Careers &amp; Enterprise Company is making excellent progress and is having a real impact across the country by linking schools and colleges with employers and providers of careers and enterprise activities. The Company is delivering lasting, powerful connections between local businesses and nearby schools and colleges through its Enterprise Adviser Network. The Company has already appointed 78 Enterprise Coordinators and almost 1,200 advisers. Over 900 schools and colleges (in 37 out of 38 Local Enterprise Partnership areas in England) have been helped to develop better careers and enterprise programmes for their pupils. In addition, the Company has launched its £5 million careers and enterprise fund to boost provision for nearly 250,000 young people across England in 75% of ‘cold spot’ areas. It has also launched a £12 million Mentoring Investment Fund to scale-up mentoring and tackle disengagement across England. Details of the Company’s achievements and progress are summarised in their first annual report published in June this year. The report can be found here: <a href="https://www.careersandenterprise.co.uk/posts/careers-enterprise-company-first-annual-review-published" target="_blank">https://www.careersandenterprise.co.uk/posts/careers-enterprise-company-first-annual-review-published</a></p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon",,"2016-10-17T15:45:13.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595584/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595584/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595584/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-07","Vocational Guidance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, when her Department plans to make available data which sets out the results achieved from the Careers and Enterprise Company investment for pupils in secondary schools and colleges.","false","Biography information for Craig Tracey","North Warwickshire","Craig Tracey","47441"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595585","Department for Education","false","2016-10-17","<p>All Government Departments are bound by legal requirements concerning the right to work in the UK and, in addition, the Civil Service Nationality Rules.</p><p> </p><p>Evidence of nationality is checked at the point of recruitment into the Civil Service as part of wider pre-employment checks, but there is no requirement on departments to retain this information beyond the point at which it has served its purpose.</p><p> </p><p>More broadly, the Government will be consulting in due course on how we work with business to ensure that workers in this country have the skills that they need to get a job. However, there are no proposals to publish lists of the number or proportion of foreign workers.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","47395 ; 47559 ; 47581","2016-10-17T16:32:55.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595585/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595585/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595585/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-07","Department for Education: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many foreign workers her Department employs.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","47412"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595586","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-12","<p>The referendum result has no immediate effect on students abroad under the Erasmus scheme or applying for 2016/17. Payments will be made in the usual way. Access to the programme after we leave the EU is a matter for the forthcoming negotiations. The Department offers the same support for study abroad under other schemes as for Erasmus.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-10-12T11:09:47.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595586/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595586/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595586/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-07","Erasmus+ Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps the Government plans to take to enable young people from the UK to take part in the Erasmus scheme after the UK has exited the EU.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","47487"
